RESOLVED on the doc-sync branch:

  - AGENTS.md gains a Documentation Synchronisation section with
    the four-track matrix (code / specs / user-manual / man), the
    install layout (bin / share/doc / share/info / share/man/man1),
    and the synchronisation rule (any change in one track requires
    matching changes in the others; drift is a review-blocking
    defect).
  - 4 hand-written man(1) pages: clautolisp, alfe, read-autolisp,
    run-alfe-conformance. Each NAME / SYNOPSIS / DESCRIPTION /
    OPTIONS / ENVIRONMENT / FILES / EXIT STATUS / SEE ALSO.
  - 18 documentation stubs (.org) for every previously-undocumented
    subproject: autolisp-runtime, autolisp-host, autolisp-mock-host,
    autolisp-builtins-core, autolisp-dcl, autolisp-init-files,
    autolisp-cli, autolisp-test, plus tool wrappers and
    autolisp-spec / alfe user-manuals. Each carries the conventional
    org-texinfo metadata (TEXINFO_FILENAME / TEXINFO_DIR_*) and
    points at the existing README / PLAN.md / source for content.
    Stubs are the structural skeleton; prose follow-ups land later.
  - clautolisp + alfe Makefiles gain a generic org -> .texi -> .info
    pipeline (%.texi: %.org via Emacs ox-texinfo; %.info: %.texi via
    makeinfo) alongside the existing %.pdf rule. make documentation
    now produces both PDF and .info for every documentation/*.org
    plus the nested subproject stubs.
  - Install layouts normalised on both:
      $(PREFIX)/bin              binaries (unchanged)
      $(PREFIX)/libexec/<sub>    support tools (unchanged)
      $(PREFIX)/share/doc/<sub>  .org + .pdf (unchanged)
      $(PREFIX)/share/info       .info + install-info dir update
      $(PREFIX)/share/man/man1   .1 man pages
    Uninstall mirrors: install-info --remove + rm man pages.

Deferred to future branches (the issue is closed once the
infrastructure + stubs land; prose fleshing is its own work):

  - Real content in the library-stub user-manuals (today they
    point at README/PLAN.md/source).
  - autolisp-spec Makefile install layout still needs the
    share/man + share/info path normalisation.
  - autolisp-test Makefile has no install target at all.
  - autolisp-reader / autolisp-file-compat already have docs
    under a different naming convention.

Version 1.0.53.

--- Original issue ---

As a user of the project, I need up-to-date documentation.

Note in CLAUDE.md that we need to keep the documentation up-to-date and synchronised.

For each subprojects, we have these items:

- code (including --help option output, and the implementation itself)
- specifications -> .org .pdf .info
- user-manual -> .org .pdf .info
- man page -> .man

A modification in one of these items, must involve an upgrade of the other items.
Eg. a change in the specifications will lead to modified code, user-manual and possibly man page.
A change in the code may need an update to the specifications and/or user-manual and man page.
etc.

Specifications gather what the program should do, for the developer of
the program.

User-manual gather all information about what the program does, and
how it's used for the user of the program.

Man page gather a description of the usage (options), and a short
description of what the program does, and the effect of each
option. It's an extract of the user-manual, between user-manual and
--help, for use at the terminal. (Often, the man page and the --help
can be very close in contents, --help is only terser in formatting.


The programs are installed in $PREFIX/bin
The user-manuals are installed along with other documents in $PREFIX/share/doc/$subproject/ but the .info of the user-manual.
The user-manual .info are installed in $PREFIX/share/info (the file $PREFIX/share/info/dir should be updated, see if there's an emacs command to do it).
The man pages are installed in $PREFIX/man/man1

1- Verify and update for each subproject the synchronism between these
   elements (add the missing elements).

2- Update the Makefiles, including the intall target.

3- take note that the synchronism must be maintained in the future at
   each modification of one or the other item.
